The recording is in progress.

2
00:00:08,262 --> 00:00:08,603
There we are.

3
00:00:09,826 --> 00:00:10,207
Very good.

4
00:00:10,266 --> 00:00:27,219
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

5
00:00:27,689 --> 00:00:40,307
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

6
00:00:41,929 --> 00:00:45,994
So I'm getting a little message here saying that the internet is unstable.

7
00:00:46,195 --> 00:00:49,899
So if I disappear, no worries, I shall reappear.

8
00:00:53,085 --> 00:01:04,322
So a couple of weeks, a couple of moons ago, I was tackling the whole idea of social conditioning and how it becomes our karma.

9
00:01:08,188 --> 00:01:09,771
Something wrong with the...

10
00:01:09,831 --> 00:01:11,694
Okay, it's a funny sound.

11
00:01:12,233 --> 00:01:20,746
And how it becomes our karma in the sense that we have to take full responsibility for the conditioning that we've been given.

12
00:01:20,912 --> 00:01:22,495
and try and sort it out.

13
00:01:23,396 --> 00:01:37,430
And then I tackle the problem of neoliberalism and how mindfulness was being used to further their agenda.

14
00:01:39,093 --> 00:01:48,742
And so the third thing to tackle, I think, which everybody's probably very concerned about, is the environment and social collapse

15
00:01:49,718 --> 00:01:58,548
So I thought I'd just give a resume of where we are, if I can, and then just say how we can approach it.

16
00:02:00,129 --> 00:02:10,600
So in 2015, the first nine months, global mean warming reached one degree centigrade above pre-industrial time.

17
00:02:10,640 --> 00:02:14,884
So that was an important moment.

18
00:02:15,445 --> 00:02:17,548
And of course, it's continuing to climb.

19
00:02:18,490 --> 00:02:26,000
In the UK here on the 19th of July, we passed 40 degrees, I think first time ever.

20
00:02:27,741 --> 00:02:35,551
And as you know, there's a huge drought at the moment all over Europe and massive floods in Australia.

21
00:02:36,312 --> 00:02:38,034
I was talking to a friend out there.

22
00:02:39,685 --> 00:02:43,471
It peaked at 14.4 meters high.

23
00:02:43,770 --> 00:02:45,092
Isn't that unbelievable?

24
00:02:45,873 --> 00:02:49,338
That's about three or four double-decker buses, isn't it?

25
00:02:49,360 --> 00:02:56,270
I believe the amount of water that must have been dropped.

26
00:02:58,073 --> 00:03:02,919
So anyway, these are all little signs preparing us for what's to come.

27
00:03:04,042 --> 00:03:07,026
And we're not seeing very much action about it.

28
00:03:08,086 --> 00:03:17,556
Reminds you a little bit about the Britain before the Second World War where Chamberlain did his best to bring about peace for our time.

29
00:03:18,437 --> 00:03:20,000
He'd lived through the First World War.

30
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:23,484
He just didn't want to see the horror of war again.

31
00:03:24,284 --> 00:03:32,253
But of course, he was duped really by Hitler and he died shortly after he declared war.

32
00:03:34,022 --> 00:03:41,212
So at the moment, we've got all these terrible things going on, apart from Ukraine, China.

33
00:03:44,236 --> 00:03:51,007
And then there's a terrible incident in America, Salman Rushdie being stabbed.

34
00:03:52,849 --> 00:03:57,756
And it was quoting him saying that he was concerned about democracy in the US.

35
00:03:58,037 --> 00:04:00,300
So I think that's there as well.

36
00:04:00,787 --> 00:04:19,175
And I think perhaps most, or should we say, most, yeah, really disturbing, let's put it that way, is the sort of general mood of the age, the sort of zeitgeist, slowly moving away from liberal democracy to illiberal democracy.

37
00:04:19,194 --> 00:04:23,502
In other words, fascism, some form of authoritarianism.

38
00:04:23,521 --> 00:04:28,870
And I think many people were shocked by this Orban movement.

39
00:04:28,850 --> 00:04:35,177
You know, saying things like we are not a mixed race and we do not want to become a mixed race.

40
00:04:35,456 --> 00:04:36,538
They are a mixed race.

41
00:04:37,338 --> 00:04:50,992
They're a combination of Huns, which were Mongoloid, and Turkic, the same people as Turkey.

42
00:04:51,874 --> 00:04:52,995
I don't know what he's going on about.

43
00:04:54,557 --> 00:04:55,718
And then, of course...

44
00:04:57,672 --> 00:05:04,002
He then went on to say that countries where European and non-Europeans mingle are no longer nations.

45
00:05:04,281 --> 00:05:07,487
And then he went off to America to give a talk to his buddies.

46
00:05:08,427 --> 00:05:25,754
So the fact that a head of state in the EU can actually say that, and obviously there'll be many people who will support him, that's the thing, really shows us where we're moving towards.

47
00:05:26,966 --> 00:05:34,654
And as these pressures grow, I'm reminded again of that poem by W.B.

48
00:05:34,714 --> 00:05:40,040
Yeats, The Second Coming, which I think I read one evening.

49
00:05:40,742 --> 00:05:48,029
And it's got this wonderful line, the best lack all conviction, while the worst are full of passionate intensity.

50
00:05:48,630 --> 00:05:50,392
So, you know, you just get the feel.

51
00:05:51,233 --> 00:05:55,437
And our reaction, well, my reaction anyway,

52
00:05:55,874 --> 00:06:10,797
I've been very gloomy and I had two or three conversations where on both occasions, on two occasions, I had to get in touch with them again and apologize for being so gloomy about the situation.

53
00:06:11,778 --> 00:06:19,350
So it's a case, I think, of beginning to realize that, you know, we have to see this situation from a spiritual point of view.

54
00:06:20,427 --> 00:06:34,490
And to deny it, to deny the thing, you know, to sort of devote ourselves to sort of escapism, sex, drugs and rock and roll, or to become despondent and uncaring, disengaged.

55
00:06:34,550 --> 00:06:40,360
I mean, that's just going to lead to some sort of despair eventually, I think.

56
00:06:42,584 --> 00:06:47,992
There's, of course, the fear that grows in us and a sense of panic.

57
00:06:48,552 --> 00:06:51,697
So, again, that can lead to even suicidal feelings.

58
00:06:53,238 --> 00:06:59,788
There was a case in 1938 where Orson Welles adapted the H.G.

59
00:06:59,829 --> 00:07:02,853
Welles War, War of the Worlds.

60
00:07:04,194 --> 00:07:09,182
And it began without telling anybody that it was a play.

61
00:07:09,365 --> 00:07:13,009
And it was done as if it was a real broadcast that the Martians had landed.

62
00:07:14,872 --> 00:07:16,896
And of course, people fled their homes.

63
00:07:17,096 --> 00:07:18,338
Lots of people fled their homes.

64
00:07:19,098 --> 00:07:22,043
Luckily, there wasn't anybody committed suicide.

65
00:07:25,026 --> 00:07:30,355
So that just shows what happens when something grips a population.

66
00:07:31,336 --> 00:07:36,603
And in a sense, we've got to tackle these things within us.

67
00:07:38,120 --> 00:07:40,904
The other, of course, major feeling might be anger.

68
00:07:40,944 --> 00:07:50,142
And I thought I would read out the discourse, the Kakachupama Sutta, which translates as the simile of the saw.

69
00:07:51,925 --> 00:08:00,802
So the Buddha says, even if bandits were to carve you up savagely, limb from limb, with a two-handed saw,

70
00:08:01,762 --> 00:08:08,630
He among you who let his heart get angered, even that would not be doing my bidding.

71
00:08:10,151 --> 00:08:11,915
Even then you should train yourselves.

72
00:08:12,595 --> 00:08:16,940
Our minds will be unaffected and we will say no evil words.

73
00:08:17,942 --> 00:08:23,588
We will remain sympathetic with a mind of goodwill and with no inner hate.

74
00:08:24,750 --> 00:08:29,997
We will keep pervading these people with an awareness imbued with goodwill and

75
00:08:30,348 --> 00:08:46,015
And beginning with them, we will keep pervading the all-encompassing world with an awareness imbued with goodwill, abundant, expansive, immeasurable, free from hostility, free from ill will.

76
00:08:46,336 --> 00:08:48,340
That's how you should train yourselves.

77
00:08:49,214 --> 00:08:53,500
Monks, if you attend, monks, by the way, just everybody, yeah?

78
00:08:53,519 --> 00:09:04,595
If you attend constantly to this admonition on the simile of the saw, do you see any aspect of speech, slight or gross, that you could not endure?

79
00:09:05,096 --> 00:09:05,615
No, Lord.

80
00:09:06,057 --> 00:09:09,741
Then attend constantly to this admonition of the simile of the saw.

81
00:09:10,442 --> 00:09:14,107
That will be for your long-term welfare and happiness.

82
00:09:14,947 --> 00:09:21,738
That is what the Blessed One said, gratified the monks, delighted in the Blessed One's words.

83
00:09:23,220 --> 00:09:32,793
Now, I once read that out in a lecture, in a talk to people, and somebody said, the Buddha had a great sense of humor.

84
00:09:37,259 --> 00:09:42,626
So that just, it's very difficult for us to follow that command.

85
00:09:43,044 --> 00:09:59,687
But in fact, all these emotional states that we might suffer from, the sense of fear, of not wanting to face reality, the realities as they come, and of the anger...

86
00:10:00,815 --> 00:10:03,580
is really to ask ourselves, in what way is it helping?

87
00:10:03,899 --> 00:10:05,143
I mean, how does it help me?

88
00:10:05,283 --> 00:10:07,385
How does it help anybody else?

89
00:10:08,067 --> 00:10:16,883
So that immediately, hopefully, cuts through the catastrophizing, you know, and just stay with the present moment, with what's actually happening.

90
00:10:19,528 --> 00:10:22,552
Even if, you know, even if...

91
00:10:22,820 --> 00:10:32,570
Millions of people start to die from lack of food, from thirst with this drought and stuff like that, overheating.

92
00:10:33,912 --> 00:10:42,900
You know, even though that looks, you know, from a total point of view, really quite apocalyptic.

93
00:10:43,782 --> 00:10:46,764
But we have to remind ourselves that we all die singly.

94
00:10:46,784 --> 00:10:48,888
We all die just ourselves.

95
00:10:48,947 --> 00:10:51,190
We're all alone when we die.

96
00:10:51,692 --> 00:10:55,197
And some will die in a very painful situation.

97
00:10:55,698 --> 00:10:57,321
Others will die in beatitude.

98
00:10:58,102 --> 00:11:03,910
So it's just recognizing that these are all still individual deaths.

99
00:11:07,196 --> 00:11:09,899
And again, you know, we're stuck with what can we do, you see.

100
00:11:10,120 --> 00:11:17,851
So you have to accept the sort of limits of our ability, of our power.

101
00:11:18,153 --> 00:11:21,881
and even of our influence, you know.

102
00:11:23,846 --> 00:11:36,297
So beginning to see this whole situation as an opportunity for spiritual growth, then at least we know we can benefit from it.

103
00:11:37,254 --> 00:11:48,426
And really come to, we might have to come to that awful realization that there's not going to be a cure for this situation and that all we can do is care.

104
00:11:49,066 --> 00:11:55,712
It's a bit like when somebody has a progressive illness or a chronic or even a terminal illness.

105
00:11:56,173 --> 00:11:57,234
There's no cure for it.

106
00:11:57,634 --> 00:12:01,158
It's just that you have, you know, but you can develop care.

107
00:12:02,099 --> 00:12:06,283
And that means friendship and at times even rejoicing.

108
00:12:07,596 --> 00:12:09,759
And of course, definitely compassion.

109
00:12:10,500 --> 00:12:14,583
And that's really where our spiritual progress, spiritual practice is taking us.

110
00:12:15,364 --> 00:12:24,413
And we have to look upon it, you know, this growing situation as an opportunity for that.

111
00:12:24,972 --> 00:12:28,636
Otherwise, I can't see anything else but despair.

112
00:12:31,339 --> 00:12:37,485
So anyway, really this talk is an introduction to

113
00:12:38,865 --> 00:12:54,587
the six forums that Noreen will be leading based on those maxims, the six maxims that were sent as a tip in the last month by Schenck and Churchill.

114
00:12:54,607 --> 00:13:00,716
And I'm also going to email you an essay that was written by Gwen Sanderson.

115
00:13:01,576 --> 00:13:04,400
So she's actually one of our trustees.

116
00:13:04,499 --> 00:13:12,551
And she's very much involved in this whole business of climate change and social breakdown.

117
00:13:12,971 --> 00:13:18,379
And there's a whole study now, a university study on collapsology.

118
00:13:19,101 --> 00:13:26,472
So she went to a meeting and was able to sort of put that down for us in an essay.

119
00:13:26,452 --> 00:13:34,443
And we thought that once that was circulated, we would have a meeting on Zoom on the 12th of September.

120
00:13:35,245 --> 00:13:45,840
And it would just be an opportunity, really, for people to share their feelings, to explore their thoughts and feelings about this.

121
00:13:45,860 --> 00:13:48,323
So that's what will happen in the near future.

122
00:13:50,706 --> 00:13:51,447
So...

123
00:13:52,407 --> 00:13:57,395
Yeah, the situation may get, well, it will get worse, won't it?

124
00:13:57,937 --> 00:13:59,900
There's no way we're going to stop it.

125
00:14:00,741 --> 00:14:15,528
So it's a case of really looking into ourselves and making that special effort to see it from a spiritual angle, to see it from a place which is going to make us have that basic hope that there is an end to suffering and that we can actually achieve it.

126
00:14:17,246 --> 00:14:32,764
Anyway, I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not doomed you too much, and that you see the light at the end of the tunnel, and that by your practice you will liberate yourself from all suffering sooner rather than later.

127
00:14:35,948 --> 00:14:37,991
Very good.

128
00:14:38,011 --> 00:14:40,875
So, we shall sit again for a while.

129
00:14:45,107 --> 00:14:47,456
and I shall stop recording.

